model.type: Cohort-component projection with user-adjustable demographic parameters
model.description: Standard demographic projection method that ages cohorts forward in 5-year steps, applying age/sex-specific survival rates (derived from life expectancy), net migration distribution (scaled from observed patterns), and fertility rates (scaled to match TFR). Births are computed from age-specific fertility rates applied to women aged 15-49. Annual years are linearly interpolated between 5-year anchor projections.

tfr.label: Total Fertility Rate
tfr.description: Average number of children per woman over her lifetime. Current Canadian TFR is at historic low of 1.25 (2024).

life_expectancy_male.label: Life Expectancy at Birth - Males
life_expectancy_male.description: Average years a newborn male is expected to live. Current ~79.5 years (2023).

life_expectancy_female.label: Life Expectancy at Birth - Females
life_expectancy_female.description: Average years a newborn female is expected to live. Current ~83.5 years (2023).

net_migration_annual.label: Net Migration (Total Annual)
net_migration_annual.description: Total net migrants per year (immigrants + net non-permanent residents - emigrants). Recent average ~770k/year (2020-2024).

steps: 1. Start with observed 2025 population by age and sex
a. Age each cohort forward one age group (e.g., 20-24  25-29)
b. Apply 5-year survival probability (derived from life expectancy input)
c. Add net migration for each age/sex group (5 years  annual distribution)
d. Compute births from fertility rates applied to women aged 15-49 (scaled by TFR input)
e. Apply infant survival to births to get 0-4 population
3. Linearly interpolate population for years between anchors
assumptions: Age-specific mortality pattern scales proportionally with life expectancy
Age/sex distribution of net migration follows observed 2020-2024 pattern
Age-specific fertility rate pattern (peak at 30-34) scales with TFR
Sex ratio at birth remains constant at 51% male / 49% female
